segments.text: This reference system card file, I presume what this is something you developed over a long period of years.
Many years.
In fact, I, you asked me if I took it with me.
I said the courage is because I had, I wrote so small.
If a student wanted to read that, I'd have to read it for him.
I used so many abbreviations and
but mainly the reference where they could go to the library and get it.
And those were published in mimeograph form and made available.
Now, what is this that was published in mimeograph form?
These cards.
The cards, I see.
The most significant ones.
One was, well, I had some that weren't worth putting on there, like newspaper, reference to newspaper clipping.

Sometimes you get into folklore stuff that way and hearsay evidence and I'd mark it whether it was research evidence or clinical evidence and because I found attorneys don't, they want that research material so I marked all those that way for my

use so you uh your your reference would be to something in in in literature whether it be a journal article or a section of a book or something oh yes i take it you are continuing to add to your file yes i haven't kept it up as well as i should uh
But every once in a while I find one.
I use four by six index cards, plain, no ruling, just plain cards.
Break them right on both sides, very small, and get the, you might say, an abstract of a sort.
Because I'm advising students as to whether it would be worthwhile.
run off, pick one by title, it'd be just a cull that would not be very desirable.
And so I would code these as to whether they're good or excellent, or poor, and for a student's guide.
Okay, the same story, I believe, said you had pioneered the development of electronics to amplify cardiac, respiratory, and peristaltic sounds.
For what, would this be used during operations on animals or just in diagnosis?
During classwork, Dr. George T. Eads, who's now head of Veterinary Science at the University of Florida,
was the one who joined me in 36.
He deserves a lot of credit for that.
The two of us worked together.
And we sought the advice of Dutch Dillingham and Electrical Engineering and others who might have had some experience with the old, with the radio station.
on recorders and amplifiers, and we followed their advice in the sound systems.
They were quality materials.
However, we did not buy one of those tape recorders.
Dutch advised us if we were going to buy.
This was back in the late 30s, early 40s.
He said the experience with the radio is that if you want a tape recorder, you better spend $1,000 for it and get a good one.
He says a lot of them are just toys.
So we never did get that one.
So what, I mean, do you... We amplified sounds, oh...
In swallowing, for example, and also in the voice box at the larynx, put it on the vocal cords.
And having to swallow water, preferably a bottle of Coke, because you'd hear those bubbles, just like a boiler factory, so to speak.
The little bubbles would pop in the stock, and you'd hear them.
and students could get those sounds that they'd never heard before because of the lack of amplification.
It was, they were very instructive tools and I went to Cornell for
by two-week workshops on two occasions.
And Dr. H. H. Dukes, who was head of Physiology at Cornell University, pioneered in the use of instruments, physical instruments and electronic instruments for teaching methods.
I gained a great deal of knowledge from those workshops.
Let me see if I can.
If you had, say, an animal that you suspected had a respiratory ailment, you could then put the equipment on that animal and listen to the animal breathe.
The whole class then can hear it.
Oh, yes.
As opposed to each one having to use a stethoscope to hear it individually.
That is right.
That's right.

It would, that way then the whole class could hear it one time and hear the entire proceedings and then would be able to remember that sound and if they heard it again in another animal they could draw a comparison between the two cases then.
Yes, there are different sounds in different animals, even in normal animals you get different sounds.
It was a near experience for them, for us too.
Is this, I take it, the same type of equipment is still being used?
Oh yes, but to get more sophisticated equipment out there now and use physiographs which developed at Baylor University in Baylor Medical College in Houston.
And we used to use the camographs, the old smoked, but put carbon, a layer of carbon on slick white paper, and then use writing points that would leave a white on black background.
But there are a lot of objections to it.
Some students would spend a lot of time smoking, and others would ruin it.

and you can teach much more with a physiograph and you can work about five students to a physiograph and of course a lot of this electronics is push button work and you need somebody to keep them working
but they have employees who take care of that.
I guess more and more come to realize since I've been here that you use a lot of the same equipment and same techniques on animals as medical doctors do on humans.
Well, there are some similarities, yes.
Electrocardiograph and electroencephalograph.
We use stethoscopes and we use other instruments, otoscopes for the ear.
And quite a bit of it is, in fact, we've purchased some from medical supply houses.
We talked a little bit earlier before we turned the machine on about the evolution of co-education at Texas A&M.
Did the School of Vet Medicine have any girls prior to the undergraduate school here at A&M having girls?
No, our first girl, I think graduated in 67, I believe.
And then we had, Perhaps you graduated in 66, and then we had about four in 67.
Now they have quite a few, around 30.
That is in one class.
So they're, what then, three classes?
Is the vet medicine degree a three year?
It's a three-year consisting of three semesters per year.
So you have three classes going at one time per second and third year?
First, second, and third years.
What was the rationale behind switching vet medicine from a semester to the trimester basis?
Greater utilization of equipment, time, and the employees were put on 12 months basis.
Some of them had previously had been on nine months.
And greater utilization of all equipment and manpower, both.
fairly sophisticated complex of buildings and machinery over there, and if you were only on two semesters per year, you had a third of the year during which it basically stands idle.
I think it's much better on a trimester than semester basis.
When you were on a semester, was it then a four-year program?
Yes, and then of course two years pre-vet and then four years veterinary medicine.
Nine months each.
Now how many years of pre-vet do you have?
They don't have a pre-vet curriculum as such.
They take 68 credit hours and they are
They're advised, they can take the pre-vet at other institutions, but they are advised to take certain courses, required courses.
But of course some of them come to us with degrees, masters and even doctorates.
And on an occasional doctorate would come, go through, but a number of them with bachelor degrees.
But say if a student comes to Texas A&M with the intention ultimately of going to vet school, he would be an undergraduate probably what, three years?
And then if he is fortunate to get into vet school?
Well 68 hours, I think he could get that and possibly less if he goes to summer school, less than three years.
So,
Of that 68 hours, you say there's no prescribed...
Yes, some prescribed courses, yes.
What I'm saying is there's no real prescribed curriculum.
There are required courses.
Yes.
About what percentage...
It's more flexible that way rather than a prescribed pre-vet program.
About what percentage of those 68 hours are required courses?

all 68 I think now wait a minute they have might have several electives in there but they have to have 68 I don't recall now the required courses that have so many hours minimum of organic chemistry a minimum of
Physics, I think eight hours of physics, and I think 10 or 12 hours of chemistry, I believe.
I don't recall now.
But, and some animal science courses.
At an earlier period, you had a prescribed two-year pre-vet course, I take it.
Oh, yes.
And then for those who were accepted to the vet school, another four years of drug medicine.
That's right.
The thing that makes it better for the student
where the prescribed pre-vet, they'd take courses they wouldn't need.
This way, they can apply most of these courses on other degree plans.
So, in other words, there were probably a number of kids who went through pre-vet and then didn't get into the vet school.
That's right.
Excuse me a minute.
Do you remember at what point this
prescribed pre-vet curriculum was discontinued?
Hasn't been too long.
Two or three years.
Two or three years, I see.
I don't recall.
So it was after you retired?
Oh yes, that's right.
Had there been some talk of discontinuing it before then?
Not that I recall.
But do you have any idea as to why it was discontinued?
No, I don't.
To help students save their time and so that they could apply that work on other degree plans if they weren't successful in getting in.
I imagine now there's only a small percentage of those who apply who actually get in, is there not?
I don't recall.
Oh, a year or two ago, I talked to one of the members of the selection committee.
One out of three or four or something like that would get in.
So 25 to 30% perhaps of those who applied get in.
I don't recall how many applicants they had last year, between 300 and 400, something like that.
I don't recall either.
I have an acquaintance who teaches over there, and I talked with him about it, but I don't remember either.
The article about which I spoke earlier, written at the time of your retirement, indicated you were the author of numerous technical publications.
When you taught as many as 20 or more hours per week, how did you find time to do research and writing?
I've been asked that question many times.
I don't know.
Did, obviously, or well, I mean it isn't obviously, I was wondering, I'm assuming that these articles are based to a certain extent upon research that you did.
Some yes, some not.
Some are just for meetings.
These would be papers presented at meetings?
Yeah, presented.
But obviously you don't just dream that information that you pass out, that you include in the papers at a meeting.
I have a bibliography.
I presented one to the American Public Health Association in Kansas City.
I had a bibliography of several hundred.
I used several hundred references to write that paper.
Well, I assume that that reference system which you devised and made available to students helped you somewhat when you sat down to do a paper.
A great deal, yes.
You could get almost immediate access to the technical literature and so forth.
Were there any other people in vet medicine who had similar reference systems?
I mean, I would assume that your reference system would primarily cover those areas of your responsibility rather than all aspects of vet medicine.
Yes, I kept one solely on toxicology.
In the early years, I had decided to keep one in physiology, one in pharmacology, one in toxicology.
Those were the three cautious areas.
I found it impossible to do.
So then I restricted myself to toxicology.
I mean, it was too much of a task to keep all three of them.
That's right.
We had good textbooks in physiology and fairly good, not as good in pharmacology as physiology, but when you have a good textbook to go by.
But when you don't have a very good textbook, that means that you...
I have to supplement this with a mimeograph material.
In fact, I had the mimeograph material for toxicology.
It was a little better than a ream of paper between 500 and 600 pages.
This was reproduced for each of the students?
Yes.
I had many calls for that.
And finally, the budget forced me to restrict it to students who took the course.
Were these calls from other campuses?
Yes, not only, in other countries too.
Well I can imagine that word gets around if you have something good.
It got to be quite a task with me.
I didn't even have my name on some of it.
An instructor left here and went to another school and one of his
co-workers used and gave him credit, and he denied it.
He said, no, that credit should be to P.W.
Burns at Texas A&M.
He's the one who worked at it.
Occasionally I put my name on some of it, some I wouldn't.
It is work that is available to anyone if you worked it out.
Yeah, yeah.
I've done some bibliographical compiling in the past.
It's an interesting chore, but it's a chore nevertheless.
And errors, you have to be very careful of errors creeping in.
Yes, you do.
What types of things have you been doing since you retired?
Oh, I did a little consulting work.
didn't care too much about it because there were potential court cases.
One of them did turn up in court.
And sometimes I was pitted against former students, and I didn't like that.
Sometimes I had former graduates on my side and some opposing, which is quite healthy, of course.
But I disliked the nature.
of the work that is controversial.
This may be treading on dangerous ground here, and I realize that where there are potential court cases involved you can't go into a great detail, but what is the nature of your consulting?
Poisons.
poisons and poisonous plants.

And then I haven't kept up with the literature in the last several years as well as I usually refer an inquiry to the department where I'm sure they've kept up with it much better in doing research work in those areas.
So
I enjoy manual labor now, have ever since I retired.
While you were still on the faculty, did you ever do any work with the experiment station, agricultural experiment station?
No, we didn't have a, we were not, they do have a connection now in the department, but not then.
Okay.
Have you done any consulting abroad, outside of the United States?
No, not on consulting cases.
I've corresponded with some.
I was wondering, I sort of asked because so many of our retired faculty people have gone abroad on AID programs or something akin to that.
Yes.
No, I have not.
Okay.
